 our established physical theories usefully approximate it? P. J. E. Peebles takes on these and other big questions about the nature of science, drawing on a lifetime of experience as a leading physicist and using cosmology as an example. He traces the history of thought about the nature of physical science since Einstein, and succinctly lays out the fundamental working assumptions. Through a careful examination of the general theory of relativity, Einstein’s cosmological principle, and the theory of an expanding universe, Peebles shows the evidence that we are discovering the nature of reality in successive approximations through increasingly demanding scrutiny.A landmark work, The Whole Truth is essential reading for anyone interested in the practice of science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCosmology. 0aPhysics. 0aReality. 0aSciencexPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / Cosmology.2bisacsh  aAbsolute magnitude.  aAcceleration.  aAngular momentum.  aApproximation.  aAstronomer.  aAstronomy.  aAsymptotically flat spacetime.  aAtomic nucleus.  aAtomic number.  aBaryon.  aBig Bang.  aCalculation.  aChronology of the universe.  aClassical limit.  aClassical physics.  aComprehension (logic).  aConservation law.  aCosmic Evolution (book).  aCosmological constant.  aCosmological principle.  aDensity.  aEmpirical research.  aEquivalence principle.  aExistence.  aExtrapolation.  aFred Hoyle.  aGalaxy cluster.  aGalaxy rotation curve.  aGeneral relativity.  aGeorge Gamow.  aGoodness of fit.  aGravitational acceleration.  aGravitational redshift.  aGravity.  aHubble's law.  aInverse-square law.  aJupiter.  aKinetic energy.  aKuiper belt.  aLength scale.  aLinear scale.  aMach's principle.  aMass distribution.  aMeasurement.  aMetric expansion 